Interrupts are signals sent to the processor by external devices or internal mechanisms to request its attention. When an interrupt occurs, the processor stops its current execution and transfers control to a specific interrupt handler.
Interrupts play a crucial role in multitasking and real-time operating systems, allowing the system to quickly respond to external events without having to poll devices continuously. Software Interrupts: Generated by software, often through system calls. Timer Interrupts: Generated by an internal timer to provide a mechanism for the operating system. Hardware Interrupts: Triggered by external devices
